1
00:00:09,790 --> 00:00:11,724
[Man]
"I do solemnly swear..."

2
00:00:11,792 --> 00:00:13,919
[Group Repeating]
"I do solemnly swear..."

3
00:00:13,994 --> 00:00:16,428
"...that I will be loyal
to the profession of medicine..."

4
00:00:16,496 --> 00:00:19,590
"...that I will be loyal
to the profession of medicine..."

5
00:00:19,666 --> 00:00:22,066
"...and just and generous
to its members,"

6
00:00:22,135 --> 00:00:25,263
"...and just and generous
to its members,"

7
00:00:25,339 --> 00:00:28,638
"...that I will prescribe regimen
for the good of my patients..."

8
00:00:28,709 --> 00:00:31,940
"...that I will prescribe regimen
for the good of my patients..."

9
00:00:32,012 --> 00:00:34,947
"...according to my ability
and my judgement,"

10
00:00:35,015 --> 00:00:38,143
"...according to my ability
and my judgement,"

11
00:00:38,218 --> 00:00:40,914
"and above all else,
first do no harm."

12
00:00:40,987 --> 00:00:44,218
"and above all else,
first do no harm."

13
00:00:46,793 --> 00:00:50,229
[Boy And Woman Laughing]

14
00:00:50,297 --> 00:00:52,288
[Woman]
Yep.

15
00:00:52,366 --> 00:00:54,926
[Boy]
That emperor marched down the street...

16
00:00:55,001 --> 00:00:57,868
...in front of all the people
wearing nothing at all?

17
00:00:57,938 --> 00:01:02,466
[Woman Laughs]
Yeah. But then a little boy whispered...

18
00:01:02,542 --> 00:01:07,070
..."But Mother, the emperor
has nothing on!"

19
00:01:07,147 --> 00:01:10,310
But see, the tailors had told him
that they made his clothes...

20
00:01:10,384 --> 00:01:13,217
...out of the most splendid cloth
in all the land...

21
00:01:13,286 --> 00:01:15,550
...and that only stupid people
couldn't see it.

22
00:01:15,622 --> 00:01:17,556
The emperor
couldn't see it...

23
00:01:17,624 --> 00:01:19,922
...but he didn't want anybody
to think he was stupid.

24
00:01:19,993 --> 00:01:24,396
The boy could see the silly emperor
didn't have any clothes on.

25
00:01:24,464 --> 00:01:27,991
- Mm-hmm.
- He believed his own eyes.

26
00:01:28,068 --> 00:01:31,663
Did the boy's mother
believe her own eyes?

27
00:01:31,738 --> 00:01:34,764
Hmm. Well, let's see.

28
00:01:34,841 --> 00:01:37,309
No, she didn't, Mommy.

29
00:01:37,377 --> 00:01:39,311
Hmm.

30
00:01:39,379 --> 00:01:41,313
Why?

31
00:01:41,381 --> 00:01:45,147
[Stammers]
Well, he was the emperor.

32
00:01:45,218 --> 00:01:47,948
Dad's home
from his poker game.

33
00:01:48,021 --> 00:01:51,957
Oh. Tell him his dinner's
in the oven.

34
00:01:53,360 --> 00:01:55,385
Mr. Turgen's with him.

35
00:01:57,898 --> 00:02:02,062
Okay, buddy.
You come on, into the beddy.

36
00:02:02,135 --> 00:02:05,434
Into the beddy. Yeah.

37
00:02:05,505 --> 00:02:08,372
[Kisses] How much do I love you?

38
00:02:08,442 --> 00:02:10,842
- More than life itself?
- Don't you forget it.

39
00:02:10,911 --> 00:02:13,641
- I want to kiss Daddy.
- When he comes up to bed.

40
00:02:13,713 --> 00:02:16,511
- I want to kiss Mark.
- Mark's doing his homework.

41
00:02:16,583 --> 00:02:19,848
- I want to kiss Lynn.
- He's all yours.

42
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:23,788
- The little bird...
- [Laughing]

43
00:02:23,857 --> 00:02:26,849
- ...is coming to say good night...
- No! No!

44
00:02:26,927 --> 00:02:29,589
- ...to the little log.
- No!

45
00:02:29,663 --> 00:02:31,893
- Say good night.
- No little bird kisses!

46
00:02:31,965 --> 00:02:35,867
The little log is gonna give
the little bird good night kisses.

47
00:02:39,206 --> 00:02:43,609
- Dave.
- Here she comes.

48
00:02:48,782 --> 00:02:50,716
Hey, Wally.

49
00:02:50,784 --> 00:02:53,548
[Clears Throat]
How are you?

50
00:02:55,922 --> 00:02:57,856
I got coffee on.

51
00:02:57,924 --> 00:03:01,553
Uhh, no, thanks.
I-I gotta get going.

52
00:03:04,965 --> 00:03:06,899
What's up?

53
00:03:06,967 --> 00:03:11,131
- [Sighs]
- Hey, Mr. Turgen. Sweet truck.

54
00:03:11,204 --> 00:03:13,138
Hi, Mark.

55
00:03:15,141 --> 00:03:19,134
[Sighs]
I lost.

56
00:03:19,212 --> 00:03:21,680
You lost.

57
00:03:21,748 --> 00:03:24,979
Yeah, well, the good thing
is who I lost to.

58
00:03:25,051 --> 00:03:27,519
Wally. He's willing
to lease it back to us.

59
00:03:27,587 --> 00:03:31,216
Lease what back to us?

60
00:03:33,560 --> 00:03:36,495
[Mark Laughing]
Good one, Dad.

61
00:03:36,563 --> 00:03:38,895
He's raggin'on you, Mom.

62
00:03:38,965 --> 00:03:43,993
If you're joking me,
Dave Reimuller, I'm gonna kill you.

63
00:03:44,070 --> 00:03:47,938
And if you're not joking me,
I'm gonna kill you. I will!

64
00:03:48,008 --> 00:03:50,306
- [All Laughing]
- Nah!

65
00:03:50,377 --> 00:03:52,868
- Not till you see what I've won.
- Oh, man!

66
00:03:55,982 --> 00:03:59,782
[Wally]
She's yours. Come on.

67
00:03:59,853 --> 00:04:01,980
[Horse Neighs]

68
00:04:02,055 --> 00:04:05,786
- Oh, no. Uh-uh.
- [Lynn] Mom!

69
00:04:05,859 --> 00:04:10,057
Oh, honey, do you have any idea how much
a horse like that is worth?

70
00:04:10,130 --> 00:04:13,099
- Wow!
- [Wally] Nothing to me. She injured
a foot as a two-year-old.

71
00:04:13,166 --> 00:04:15,396
She'll never make
a field hunter.

72
00:04:15,468 --> 00:04:19,427
- You could still ride her. [Sighs]
- Mom, please!

73
00:04:19,506 --> 00:04:21,872
As deputy sheriff
and town councilman...

74
00:04:21,942 --> 00:04:24,001
...I order you to take her.

75
00:04:24,077 --> 00:04:26,409
Hey, there, cowpokes!
I'm gonna ride him first!

76
00:04:26,479 --> 00:04:29,414
- Hey!
- Hey, what are you doing outta bed?

77
00:04:29,482 --> 00:04:33,509
Well, you can't sleep now.
Okay, big fella, mount up.

78
00:04:33,587 --> 00:04:37,489
- I'm going to call him "Schwartz".
- Schwartz?

79
00:04:37,557 --> 00:04:39,582
What kind of name
is Schwartz?

80
00:04:39,659 --> 00:04:41,923
I'm sure she already
has a name, Robbie.

81
00:04:41,995 --> 00:04:45,931
Mrs. Schwartz is Robbie's favorite
preschool teacher. Right, honey?

82
00:04:45,999 --> 00:04:49,264
- Schwartz likes me.
- [Neighs]

83
00:04:49,336 --> 00:04:52,362
- [Laughing]
- I guess you can't fight
City Hall, you know?

84
00:04:52,439 --> 00:04:53,963
[Wally]
No,you can't.

85
00:04:55,075 --> 00:04:59,011
- Mr. Turgen gave us this.
- [Mom] Ohh.

86
00:04:59,079 --> 00:05:01,877
It was taken
at the Vilas County Fair.

87
00:05:01,948 --> 00:05:04,940
I just don't feel right
about taking her.

88
00:05:05,018 --> 00:05:08,249
Well, Wally wanted you to have her.
That's how come he put her in the pot.

89
00:05:08,321 --> 00:05:10,653
[Sighs]
How'd you know you'd win?

90
00:05:10,724 --> 00:05:13,625
I always win.
That's why they call me "Lucky Dave".

91
00:05:13,693 --> 00:05:17,094
- [All Laughing]
- [Schwartz Whinnies]

92
00:05:17,163 --> 00:05:19,358
How much have we got?

93
00:05:19,432 --> 00:05:23,562
Oh, about $600
less than we need.

94
00:05:23,637 --> 00:05:26,834
Great. I'll be taking
my grandchildren to Hawaii.

95
00:05:26,906 --> 00:05:29,204
Why would Wally
want to give me his horse?

96
00:05:29,275 --> 00:05:33,177
- [Schwartz Whinnies]
- He has a thing for you.

97
00:05:33,246 --> 00:05:35,806
- Oh, David!
- [Whinnying Continues]

98
00:05:35,882 --> 00:05:39,249
She's lonely, Mom. Listen to her. Can I
go out and keep her company a while?

99
00:05:39,319 --> 00:05:41,719
No, you can go up to bed.
Both of you.

100
00:05:41,788 --> 00:05:44,222
[Groans]

101
00:05:45,659 --> 00:05:47,854
- Can't I watch TV?
- Mm-mm.

102
00:05:47,927 --> 00:05:50,987
- Give me a kiss.
- Thanks, Dad.

103
00:05:51,064 --> 00:05:54,124
- Good night, Dad.
- Oh!

104
00:05:54,200 --> 00:05:59,433
You know, you've completely ruined your
daughter's chances for a happy marriage.

105
00:05:59,506 --> 00:06:04,842
Where on earth is she gonna find
a guy who'll win her dream horse
in a poker game?

106
00:06:04,911 --> 00:06:07,539
Well...

107
00:06:07,614 --> 00:06:11,550
what have I done for my chances
for a happy marriage?

108
00:06:11,618 --> 00:06:14,587
[Laughing]

109
00:06:14,654 --> 00:06:17,555
Mmm.

110
00:06:17,624 --> 00:06:21,390
I take it back. This is why
they call me "Lucky Dave".

111
00:06:21,461 --> 00:06:24,259
- [Laughs]
- [Whinnying Continues]

112
00:06:24,330 --> 00:06:26,730
[Grunts]

113
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:29,200
Oh, maybe Lynn's right.

114
00:06:29,269 --> 00:06:33,262
Maybe I should go bed down in her stall
just for the first night.

115
00:06:33,339 --> 00:06:37,036
- [Sighs]
- Or you were hoping
I'd bed down in yours?

116
00:06:37,110 --> 00:06:39,874
- Yes.
- Show a little appreciation?

117
00:06:39,946 --> 00:06:43,780
- Somethin' like that.
- Oh, sorry, Schwartz.

118
00:06:43,850 --> 00:06:46,580
[Man On Radio] Kansas City's
number-one-rated country music--

119
00:06:46,653 --> 00:06:48,917
[Lynn]
Mom, do you know where my backpack is?

120
00:06:48,988 --> 00:06:51,582
[Mom] No. You think back
to where you last saw it.

121
00:06:51,658 --> 00:06:54,218
- [Dog Barking, Chickens Clucking]
- [Lynn] Found it!

122
00:06:54,294 --> 00:06:56,592
- Did you make your bed?
- I'll do it before we leave.

123
00:06:56,663 --> 00:06:59,097
- Hey, Mom, I want to ride Schwartz.
- A little later.

124
00:06:59,165 --> 00:07:01,258
- You said I could ride him.
- Yeah.

125
00:07:01,334 --> 00:07:03,529
- It's a her.
- How do you know?

126
00:07:03,603 --> 00:07:05,628
After school you can.

127
00:07:05,705 --> 00:07:08,538
- Promise?
- Uh-huh. Scout's honor.

128
00:07:08,608 --> 00:07:10,872
Get the oil changed
in the car today.

129
00:07:10,944 --> 00:07:13,606
Yeah. I'll drop it off
on my way.

130
00:07:13,680 --> 00:07:17,582
Okay, troops...
we have five minutes.

131
00:07:17,650 --> 00:07:19,982
[Man On Radio, Indistinct]

132
00:07:20,053 --> 00:07:22,578
Ooh! Strong, darlin'.

133
00:07:22,655 --> 00:07:27,217
- Fertilizer should be in
in a couple of weeks.
- Good.

134
00:07:27,293 --> 00:07:31,195
And you can tell Nancy that--
[Continues, Indistinct]

135
00:07:31,264 --> 00:07:33,459
Thanks, Lori.
See you next week.

136
00:07:33,533 --> 00:07:35,467
- Hey, Doc.
- Hey, Lori.

137
00:07:35,535 --> 00:07:37,730
Looks like the airline's
got you busy.

138
00:07:37,804 --> 00:07:40,238
Yeah, I'm flying
K.C.-Denver-San Francisco this month.

139
00:07:40,306 --> 00:07:43,605
- And I'm plantin' my crops
whenever I have a few minutes.
- Ooh.

140
00:07:43,676 --> 00:07:45,906
So, are you still
seein' patients too?

141
00:07:45,979 --> 00:07:48,072
Not for years.
That was another life.

142
00:07:48,148 --> 00:07:51,413
I wouldn't know a stethoscope if it
jumped up and strangled me.

143
00:07:51,484 --> 00:07:54,681
Oh, I hear you have a new mouth to feed
over at your place.

144
00:07:54,754 --> 00:07:57,086
- [Phone Rings]
- Wally Turgen's hunter.

145
00:07:57,157 --> 00:07:59,523
- [Woman] Old Mill Hardware.
- Where'd you hear that?

146
00:07:59,592 --> 00:08:03,187
- Paperboy this morning.
- Oh. Grapevine must be slippin'.

147
00:08:03,263 --> 00:08:07,199
We had her at least seven hours by then.
[Laughs]

148
00:08:07,267 --> 00:08:11,465
Lori, that was Robbie's school.
He took a tumble.

149
00:08:11,538 --> 00:08:14,701
He's okay, but they
want you to check it out.

150
00:08:14,774 --> 00:08:17,572
[Sighs]
Oh, okay. Oh! My car's in the shop.

151
00:08:17,644 --> 00:08:21,375
- You need a ride over there?
- Is that all right?

152
00:08:21,447 --> 00:08:25,042
Thanks. I really
appreciate this, Doc.

153
00:08:25,118 --> 00:08:27,552
[Children Playing,
Laughing]

154
00:08:27,620 --> 00:08:30,214
Well, I wouldn't have bothered you
except for the way he fell.

155
00:08:30,290 --> 00:08:32,554
He was taking
a snack plate to the trash...

156
00:08:32,625 --> 00:08:34,889
- and it seemed like he
just kind of collapsed.
- Uh-huh.

157
00:08:34,961 --> 00:08:37,896
But he got right up,
and he's been fine ever since.

158
00:08:37,964 --> 00:08:40,091
Hey, how come you
fell down, kiddo?

159
00:08:40,166 --> 00:08:43,567
- I didn't fall down.
- Well, I'll give
his pediatrician a call.

160
00:08:43,636 --> 00:08:47,231
-I made a picture of the emperor. See?
-The emperor?

161
00:08:47,307 --> 00:08:50,674
- Oh, that's goo--
- No. Like this.

162
00:08:50,743 --> 00:08:55,442
Oh, that-- Yeah.
Well, I like it better the other way.

163
00:08:56,950 --> 00:08:59,248
[Laughs]
He's okay, I think.

164
00:08:59,319 --> 00:09:01,879
Hey, Dr. Peterson, do you
want to see my picture?

165
00:09:05,758 --> 00:09:08,522
[Neighing]

166
00:09:10,230 --> 00:09:12,425
Hey, Mom!
I wanna ride Schwartz!

167
00:09:12,498 --> 00:09:17,060
- She's not ready yet.
- I'm ready now!

168
00:09:17,136 --> 00:09:19,400
When we're done
lunging her you can.

169
00:09:19,472 --> 00:09:22,100
You promised.
Scout's honor!

170
00:09:22,175 --> 00:09:24,473
[Laughs]
Oh, oh! Wait. No, wait.

171
00:09:24,544 --> 00:09:27,536
We gotta get the beans out of Schwartz
before we put you on her.

172
00:09:27,614 --> 00:09:30,378
Don't want to have
two matching shiners, do we?

173
00:09:30,450 --> 00:09:35,114
Hey, Mark, I got a world-class
assistant truck washer here.

174
00:09:35,188 --> 00:09:38,783
- Happens to have an opening
in his schedule.
- [Whinnies]

175
00:09:40,226 --> 00:09:42,251
All right, squirt.

176
00:09:42,328 --> 00:09:44,888
- Hey, stop calling me squirt!
- Mark.

177
00:09:44,964 --> 00:09:49,401
Fine. When I finish washing a spot,
you rinse it off.

178
00:09:49,469 --> 00:09:52,199
Oh, but, whatever you do,
don't do this.

179
00:09:52,272 --> 00:09:54,763
[Gasps] Hey, quit it!
Mom, Mark squirted me!

180
00:09:54,841 --> 00:09:56,775
Mark, be nice
to your brother.

181
00:09:58,544 --> 00:10:00,569
Sorry.
Here you go, squirt.

182
00:10:00,647 --> 00:10:03,480
You told me to squirt!

183
00:10:05,218 --> 00:10:07,948
Ohhh, I'm drenched.

184
00:10:08,021 --> 00:10:12,048
You know I'm just gonna have to get you
back double for what you did to me.

185
00:10:12,125 --> 00:10:14,423
I'm comin'.

186
00:10:14,494 --> 00:10:17,554
Robbie? Robbie,
quit screwing around.

187
00:10:17,630 --> 00:10:20,599
- [Robbie Whimpering]
- That's it.

188
00:10:20,667 --> 00:10:23,227
- Robbie?
- [Whimpering Continues]

189
00:10:23,303 --> 00:10:26,898
Mom! Mom! Mom, come quick!
Something's wrong with Robbie!

190
00:10:26,973 --> 00:10:28,941
Hurry, Mom! Hurry!

191
00:10:29,008 --> 00:10:31,772
Mom!

192
00:10:31,844 --> 00:10:35,280
[Whimpering Continues]

193
00:10:35,348 --> 00:10:38,806
Oh, Robbie, Robbie.
It's okay.

194
00:10:38,885 --> 00:10:42,480
- [Whimpering Continues]
- It's okay. It's okay.

195
00:10:42,555 --> 00:10:44,853
It's okay.

196
00:10:44,924 --> 00:10:46,858
It's okay.

197
00:10:48,861 --> 00:10:53,127
[Siren Wailing]

198
00:11:02,442 --> 00:11:05,707
He was admitted 45 minutes ago,
and he's still post-stictal.

199
00:11:05,778 --> 00:11:08,474
Lori, Dave,
this is Dr. Neaves...

200
00:11:08,548 --> 00:11:10,277
-the ped's neurological consultant here.
-Hi.

201
00:11:10,350 --> 00:11:13,285
- Hi.
- He knows a lot about epilepsy.

202
00:11:13,353 --> 00:11:15,787
Epilepsy?

203
00:11:15,855 --> 00:11:18,221
Uh, yes. One seizure
is just a seizure...

204
00:11:18,291 --> 00:11:20,418
...but two, by definition,
is epilepsy.

205
00:11:20,493 --> 00:11:22,427
But he's only had one.

206
00:11:22,495 --> 00:11:25,487
The fall you called me about
this morning was probably
another kind of seizure.

207
00:11:25,565 --> 00:11:28,796
So we're going to admit him and
watch him for a couple of days.

208
00:11:28,868 --> 00:11:31,803
But this is a kid who
hardly catches a cold.

209
00:11:31,871 --> 00:11:33,862
How could he
have epilepsy?

210
00:11:33,940 --> 00:11:36,602
Well, there's a lot of different
triggers for seizure disorders.

211
00:11:36,676 --> 00:11:40,806
We're gonna run some tests
and see what we can find out.

212
00:11:40,880 --> 00:11:43,405
[Dr. Neaves] I think the best way
to understand what a seizure is...

213
00:11:43,483 --> 00:11:46,975
...is to think of it as
a short-circuit in Robbie's brain.

214
00:11:47,053 --> 00:11:49,613
Something interferes
with the normal electrical flow...

215
00:11:49,689 --> 00:11:52,180
...and everything goes
temporarily haywire.

216
00:11:52,258 --> 00:11:55,159
Oh, oh, oh. It's okay. It's okay.
Look at you so brave.

217
00:11:59,866 --> 00:12:01,891
[Dr. Neaves] Now,
Robbie's going to need a CATscan...

218
00:12:01,968 --> 00:12:05,563
...so we can see if his seizures have
a cause that we can treat surgically.

219
00:12:07,140 --> 00:12:09,904
We'll inject a dye
while his head is being X-rayed...

220
00:12:09,976 --> 00:12:12,001
...and then a computer
takes a picture...

221
00:12:12,078 --> 00:12:14,672
...just as if we'd cut
a slice of the brain.

222
00:12:14,747 --> 00:12:18,183
[Tapping Computer Keys]

223
00:12:20,853 --> 00:12:25,790
The EEG is used for comparison if
Robbie's seizures change in character.

224
00:12:25,858 --> 00:12:29,624
It's helpful in diagnosing
some special forms of epilepsy.

225
00:12:29,695 --> 00:12:34,098
We do these tests to find out
if your son has a tumor
or lesion in his brain.

226
00:12:37,837 --> 00:12:42,297
- A spinal tap is used to rule out
bacterial meningitis.
- Hold him just like that.

227
00:12:42,375 --> 00:12:45,003
If we catch it early, it can easily
be treated with antibiotics.

228
00:12:45,078 --> 00:12:48,013
- [Screaming]
- Usually we don't find anything.

229
00:12:48,081 --> 00:12:51,050
[Screaming Continues]

230
00:12:54,187 --> 00:12:56,985
We don't necessarily
need to find a cause.

231
00:12:57,056 --> 00:13:01,049
Most of the time we don't.
But we do have effective drugs.

232
00:13:01,127 --> 00:13:03,891
As a matter of fact, 70 percent
of kids with epilepsy...

233
00:13:03,963 --> 00:13:07,558
...have their seizures reasonably
controlled with the first medicine.

234
00:13:07,633 --> 00:13:09,965
We'll start Robbie
with phenobarbital.

235
00:13:10,036 --> 00:13:12,596
It's been around the longest,
so we know the most about it.

236
00:13:12,672 --> 00:13:16,039
Although it can cause
behavioral problems...

237
00:13:16,109 --> 00:13:19,670
...and is associated with withdrawal
symptoms and lowered I.Q....

238
00:13:19,745 --> 00:13:23,806
...most kids on phenobarbital
do just fine.

239
00:13:23,883 --> 00:13:27,080
- It's boring!
- "And the emperor--"
Oh, Robbie, come on.

240
00:13:27,153 --> 00:13:29,815
I don't wanna read!
It's boring. I hate it.

241
00:13:29,889 --> 00:13:32,357
- I know. All right. You just--
- I hate it!

242
00:13:32,425 --> 00:13:35,155
- I wanna ride my bike!
- You can't ride your bike, honey.

243
00:13:35,228 --> 00:13:39,130
I told you that. Because we don't
want you to fall down and hit your head.

244
00:13:39,198 --> 00:13:41,598
- I wanna go ride Schwartz!
- [Knocking]

245
00:13:41,667 --> 00:13:44,101
- You can't ride Schwartz.
I told you, sweetie.
- I wanna go pet him!

246
00:13:44,170 --> 00:13:46,604
- [Woman] Anybody home!
- Let's go see who this is.

247
00:13:46,672 --> 00:13:48,640
Come on.
Maybe it's the emperor.

248
00:13:48,708 --> 00:13:51,074
- Hey!
- It's just Margeen.

249
00:13:51,144 --> 00:13:54,739
- Well, nice to see you too, Robbie.
- [Indistinct Shouting]

250
00:13:54,814 --> 00:13:59,342
You can go play upstairs
in your room quietly, but no jumping.

251
00:13:59,418 --> 00:14:01,784
- [Shouting]
- You hear me?

252
00:14:01,854 --> 00:14:03,788
[Coughs, Chuckles]

253
00:14:03,856 --> 00:14:05,881
I ran into
Doc Peterson today.

254
00:14:05,958 --> 00:14:08,324
He wanted to know if Robbie's okay after
the fall he took at school.

255
00:14:08,394 --> 00:14:11,693
I told him I wouldn't know
since I hadn't seen you in a dog's age.

256
00:14:11,764 --> 00:14:13,698
Where have you been?

257
00:14:13,766 --> 00:14:16,064
Home, with Robbie.

258
00:14:16,135 --> 00:14:18,968
What's the matter with him?

259
00:14:19,038 --> 00:14:21,632
Well, they're not sure.

260
00:14:21,707 --> 00:14:25,040
Probably just a virus.
[Sighs]

261
00:14:25,111 --> 00:14:28,444
He's on medication, but it's--
he's having a reaction to it.

262
00:14:28,514 --> 00:14:30,573
- Coffee?
- Sure.

263
00:14:30,650 --> 00:14:33,448
What kind of reaction?

264
00:14:33,519 --> 00:14:37,250
Well... he won't eat,
can't sleep...

265
00:14:37,323 --> 00:14:40,884
...and he thinks that he can leap
tall furniture in a single bound.

266
00:14:40,960 --> 00:14:43,656
[Laughs]
What kind of medicine is he on?

267
00:14:43,729 --> 00:14:46,596
What!
[Sighs]

268
00:14:46,666 --> 00:14:49,601
Our insurance company's
computer...

269
00:14:49,669 --> 00:14:53,867
...is unable to handle the fact
that Dave has transferred union locals.

270
00:14:53,940 --> 00:14:58,172
So I submit a bill;
they send it back to me.

271
00:14:58,244 --> 00:15:00,872
I resubmit it;
they send it back to me.

272
00:15:00,947 --> 00:15:03,472
- I mean, it's--
- [Clattering]

273
00:15:03,549 --> 00:15:06,347
- Want me to go check on him?
- No, it's all right.

274
00:15:06,419 --> 00:15:09,354
I'll go up myself
in a second.

275
00:15:09,422 --> 00:15:12,858
[Sighing]
What's new?

276
00:15:12,925 --> 00:15:16,452
- [Loud Clattering, Glass Breaking]
- Robbie!

277
00:15:19,165 --> 00:15:21,292
- Check his room.
- Okay.

278
00:15:21,367 --> 00:15:24,962
[Gasps]
Robbie!

279
00:15:25,037 --> 00:15:27,938
Hey! How are you--
Come back here!

280
00:15:28,007 --> 00:15:30,441
- Come here, sweetie.
- You'll never catch me!

281
00:15:30,509 --> 00:15:33,478
- Ohh! Rob!
- I'm too speedy!

282
00:15:33,546 --> 00:15:36,982
[Indistinct Shouting]

283
00:15:37,049 --> 00:15:40,849
- Come here, honey!
- [Crying]

284
00:15:40,920 --> 00:15:44,048
- Ohhh!
- Oh! Ow! It hurts!

285
00:15:44,123 --> 00:15:46,990
[Crying Continues]

286
00:15:47,059 --> 00:15:50,927
It's okay.
It's all right.

287
00:15:50,997 --> 00:15:53,488
- It's okay. Stay here.
- Ow! It hurts!

288
00:15:53,566 --> 00:15:56,660
- I know, I know, I know, I know.
- [Crying Continues]

289
00:15:56,736 --> 00:16:00,137
[Margeen Muttering]

290
00:16:02,541 --> 00:16:05,101
I want my Mom!

291
00:16:05,177 --> 00:16:07,441
Hello, this is Lori Reimuller...
S
292
00:16:07,513 --> 00:16:11,847
...and I need to talk to Dr. Miller
about Robbie's medication.

293
00:16:11,917 --> 00:16:14,579
[Panting]
Now!

294
00:16:17,490 --> 00:16:21,551
[Robbie Singing] #A, B, C, D, E, F, G
H, I, J, K, L-M-N-O, P#

295
00:16:21,627 --> 00:16:26,564
- Hey, when's this new stuff--
What's it called?
- [Lori] Dilantin.

296
00:16:26,632 --> 00:16:29,430
- ##[Robbie Continues]
- When's this Dilantin
supposed to kick in?

297
00:16:29,502 --> 00:16:31,902
Oh, about a week.

298
00:16:31,971 --> 00:16:34,565
They're tapering off
the phenobarb...

299
00:16:34,640 --> 00:16:38,736
...and they're getting the Dilantin
up to a level where it'll work.

300
00:16:38,811 --> 00:16:42,247
What did he do? Break every bottle
of perfume in the house?

301
00:16:42,315 --> 00:16:44,408
This place smells
like a brothel.

302
00:16:44,483 --> 00:16:47,782
Hmm. Not that you'd know
what a brothel smelled like.

303
00:16:47,853 --> 00:16:50,378
- #Q R, S, T, U, V, W, X, Y, Z#
- [Laughs]

304
00:16:50,456 --> 00:16:53,948
- #Now I know my ABC's
Tell me what you think of me#
- Has it been that long?

305
00:16:54,026 --> 00:16:57,257
#A, B, C, D, E, F, G
H, I, J, K, L-M-N-O, P#

306
00:16:57,330 --> 00:16:59,992
#Q R, S, T, U, V
W, X, Y, Z#

307
00:17:00,066 --> 00:17:03,729
- It'll never be that long.
- #Now I know my ABC's, Next time
won't you sing with me#

308
00:17:03,803 --> 00:17:07,569
On the other hand...
it has been a while.

309
00:17:07,640 --> 00:17:09,574
Mmm.

310
00:17:11,744 --> 00:17:14,008
[Whispers]
Listen.

311
00:17:15,381 --> 00:17:18,111
He's okay.

312
00:17:18,184 --> 00:17:20,880
Don't let your imagination
run away with you.

313
00:17:20,953 --> 00:17:23,217
You'll drive yourself crazy.

314
00:17:23,289 --> 00:17:25,223
[Laughs]
Yeah.

315
00:17:25,291 --> 00:17:29,557
[Sighs]
Come on.

316
00:17:41,640 --> 00:17:44,108
Peanut.

317
00:17:44,176 --> 00:17:46,235
Be careful.
You'll wake him.

318
00:17:47,813 --> 00:17:51,715
I'm just gonna--
I'm just gonna cover him up...

319
00:17:51,784 --> 00:17:54,344
...make him cozy.

320
00:18:05,364 --> 00:18:07,423
[Sighs]

321
00:18:10,202 --> 00:18:12,466
[Sighs]

322
00:18:24,417 --> 00:18:26,612
This is embarrassing.

323
00:18:26,685 --> 00:18:29,882
What do you mean bringing home
a report card like this?

324
00:18:29,955 --> 00:18:33,322
No kid of mine is gonna do
better than I did in school. [Chuckles]

325
00:18:33,392 --> 00:18:36,327
- Don't have to make A's to do that.
- Well--

326
00:18:36,395 --> 00:18:39,728
- [Rooster Crows]
- You have me to make you look good.

327
00:18:42,368 --> 00:18:44,632
[Schwartz Whinnying]

328
00:18:46,038 --> 00:18:48,097
I hate grammar! It's boring!

329
00:18:48,174 --> 00:18:50,472
Well, no argument there.

330
00:18:50,543 --> 00:18:53,774
Um, what would make it
less boring?

331
00:18:53,846 --> 00:18:57,111
- If Miss Kirchwall taught naked.
- [Laughing]

332
00:18:57,183 --> 00:18:59,777
- Gross!
- [Laughing Continues]

333
00:19:01,187 --> 00:19:03,485
[Dave Sighs]

334
00:19:03,556 --> 00:19:06,753
For a year I've been putting money away
to buy your mom a good horse.

335
00:19:06,826 --> 00:19:09,260
Now we've got Schwartz.

336
00:19:09,328 --> 00:19:13,162
- I want to ride him.
- Mm-hmm.

337
00:19:13,232 --> 00:19:17,362
How boring would it be
if I added that money to the trip jar...

338
00:19:17,436 --> 00:19:20,530
...and booked us
to Hawaii next month?

339
00:19:20,606 --> 00:19:23,837
And there was even enough
money left over for, um...

340
00:19:23,909 --> 00:19:27,174
...scuba diving lessons
when we got there?

341
00:19:27,246 --> 00:19:29,339
[Laughs]

342
00:19:29,415 --> 00:19:33,784
Bring your grades up
to a mere... "B", and it's a deal.

343
00:19:33,853 --> 00:19:37,949
- I'll help you.
- Whoa. Grammar rules!

344
00:19:38,023 --> 00:19:40,457
[Laughs]

345
00:19:40,526 --> 00:19:43,222
Incentive.

346
00:19:43,295 --> 00:19:45,923
Bribery.

347
00:19:50,302 --> 00:19:53,863
- [Knocking]
- Oh. We're closed!

348
00:19:53,939 --> 00:19:56,840
[Knocking]

349
00:19:56,909 --> 00:19:59,742
Sorry, we're cl--
[Frustrated Grunt]

350
00:20:03,115 --> 00:20:05,049
- Sorry, we're closed.
- Lori?

351
00:20:05,117 --> 00:20:07,449
- Yeah.
- Bob Purdue. High school.

352
00:20:07,520 --> 00:20:09,784
I was a couple years
ahead of you.

353
00:20:09,855 --> 00:20:13,347
- Oh, yeah.
- Can I talk to you for a minute?

354
00:20:13,425 --> 00:20:15,359
Sure.

355
00:20:16,729 --> 00:20:18,663
- So how you been?
- Good.

356
00:20:18,731 --> 00:20:20,665
How's your boy, Robbie?

357
00:20:20,733 --> 00:20:23,258
[Stammers]
Uh, h-how do you know Robbie?

358
00:20:23,335 --> 00:20:26,270
I was in here a couple of months ago.
He was being your little helper.

359
00:20:26,338 --> 00:20:29,273
- He took me right over
to the garden tools.
- [Laughs]

360
00:20:29,341 --> 00:20:31,434
I'm sorry I didn't
recognize you then.

361
00:20:31,510 --> 00:20:33,705
Oh, that's all right.
You were busy.

362
00:20:33,779 --> 00:20:37,271
Such an ugly disease for such a sweet
little guy to have, isn't it?

363
00:20:37,349 --> 00:20:39,613
Epilepsy.

364
00:20:41,153 --> 00:20:43,883
Who told you
Robbie had epilepsy?

365
00:20:43,956 --> 00:20:46,220
I saw his prescription
at the pharmacy.

366
00:20:46,292 --> 00:20:49,728
I've taken the same drugs.
I've had epilepsy since I was four.

367
00:20:51,630 --> 00:20:53,757
So you hide it?

368
00:20:53,832 --> 00:20:57,598
No. Actually, they're not
even sure Robbie has epilepsy.

369
00:20:57,670 --> 00:21:00,798
- [Scoffs]
- He's only had a few episodes.

370
00:21:00,873 --> 00:21:04,434
Doctors are talking about
taking him off medication.

371
00:21:04,510 --> 00:21:06,978
You sound a little
like my parents.

372
00:21:07,046 --> 00:21:09,412
They still won't say
the word "epilepsy."

373
00:21:09,481 --> 00:21:13,178
They call it "Bob's spells"
or "Bob's condition".

374
00:21:13,252 --> 00:21:15,413
I don't remember 'em
using the word "episodes",

375
00:21:15,487 --> 00:21:17,614
but I'm sure they threw
that one in there too.

376
00:21:17,690 --> 00:21:19,624
What did you want
to talk to me about?

377
00:21:19,692 --> 00:21:22,525
Lori, I know this seems
like none of my business...

378
00:21:22,595 --> 00:21:25,428
...but Robbie's gonna need
a strong ally.

379
00:21:25,497 --> 00:21:29,991
Robbie's got plenty of allies.
He's got his family, and he's
got some really good doctors.

380
00:21:30,069 --> 00:21:33,436
But no doctor knows
what makes a seizure start or stop.

381
00:21:33,505 --> 00:21:38,169
No doctor knows why the drugs work on
some people and not on others.

382
00:21:38,243 --> 00:21:42,145
So your child becomes something of a
laboratory. They type-treat the drugs.

383
00:21:42,214 --> 00:21:45,308
- [Phone Ringing]
- That means they start
with a low dosage.

384
00:21:45,384 --> 00:21:49,320
Then they crank it up until
either the seizures go away
or your boy becomes toxic.

385
00:21:49,388 --> 00:21:53,552
- I think you better go now.
- If you place Robbie's health
entirely in their hands--

386
00:21:53,626 --> 00:21:55,560
Robbie is gonna be
just fine.

387
00:21:55,628 --> 00:21:59,689
[Lynn Crying On Phone]
Mom, if you're there,
pick up, please! Mom!

388
00:21:59,765 --> 00:22:02,757
- Lynn?
- Mom, Robbie's had a horrible seizure!

389
00:22:02,835 --> 00:22:06,236
- What?
- He stopped breathing.

390
00:22:06,305 --> 00:22:09,206
They took him to the hospital.
Dad went with them.

391
00:22:09,274 --> 00:22:11,538
Well, take Mark
and go to Margeen.

392
00:22:11,610 --> 00:22:14,272
Mom, is he gonna die?

393
00:22:14,346 --> 00:22:17,713
No, he's not going to die.

394
00:22:17,783 --> 00:22:20,251
The keys?

395
00:22:20,319 --> 00:22:23,288
[Keys Jingling]

396
00:22:24,423 --> 00:22:26,983
Get out!

397
00:22:28,560 --> 00:22:30,926
[Engine Starts]

398
00:22:30,996 --> 00:22:33,658
[Tires Screeching]

399
00:22:37,336 --> 00:22:39,668
[Dave]
Do you want to double-check?

400
00:22:39,738 --> 00:22:42,263
[Woman] You're positive that
your company's kept up...

401
00:22:42,341 --> 00:22:44,605
...on the contributions
to your health plan?

402
00:22:44,677 --> 00:22:48,613
It's a major contractor.
It's not some fly-by-night operation.

403
00:22:49,748 --> 00:22:52,876
[Chattering,
Children Crying]

404
00:22:52,951 --> 00:22:55,784
- Hi. I'm Dr. Brown.
- Hi. How do you do?

405
00:22:55,854 --> 00:22:57,981
How are you doing?

406
00:22:58,057 --> 00:23:02,255
Oooh, doesn't look like
we're havin' fun yet.

407
00:23:02,327 --> 00:23:05,091
Let's see if we can't
do somethin' about that.

408
00:23:05,164 --> 00:23:08,827
All right, I want you to follow my
finger, okay? With your eyes.

409
00:23:08,901 --> 00:23:13,201
So, Robbie was admitted
with idiopathic epilepsy?

410
00:23:13,272 --> 00:23:15,502
"Idiopathic"?

411
00:23:15,574 --> 00:23:17,735
Of uncertain origin.

412
00:23:17,810 --> 00:23:21,576
Oh. He had a grand mal seizure
with a respiratory arrest.

413
00:23:21,647 --> 00:23:25,014
And since then he's had
three more grand mals...

414
00:23:25,084 --> 00:23:27,746
...plus some other kinds too.

415
00:23:27,820 --> 00:23:30,755
Hmm, hey, the good news:

416
00:23:30,823 --> 00:23:33,758
You'll never have to worry about
Robbie being in the military.

417
00:23:33,826 --> 00:23:35,760
They won't take him.

418
00:23:35,828 --> 00:23:38,626
[Sighs] He was transferred here
to see a specialist.

419
00:23:38,697 --> 00:23:40,961
Dr. Stanfield.
He's the best.

420
00:23:41,033 --> 00:23:44,196
- [Groans]
- Okay.

421
00:23:45,838 --> 00:23:49,934
Did we talk to you about
compassionate use programs?

422
00:23:50,008 --> 00:23:52,408
"Compassionate use"?

423
00:23:52,478 --> 00:23:54,605
During the testing period
for a new drug...

424
00:23:54,680 --> 00:23:57,444
if it shows promise, the government will
approve its use for select people...

425
00:23:57,516 --> 00:23:59,780
...who aren't part
of the official study.

426
00:23:59,852 --> 00:24:02,821
That's something Dr. Stanfield
may recommend you look into.

427
00:24:02,888 --> 00:24:05,413
Mm-hmm.

428
00:24:05,491 --> 00:24:07,982
See, times have changed
in medicine.

429
00:24:08,060 --> 00:24:11,587
It's not just up to the doctor.
We look to the parents
to help chart the course.

430
00:24:11,663 --> 00:24:13,824
It's called
"joint decision making".

431
00:24:13,899 --> 00:24:17,130
Great. So do we have to wait
for Dr. Stanfield?

432
00:24:17,202 --> 00:24:20,228
Only until tomorrow morning.

433
00:24:21,840 --> 00:24:24,741
Okay. Thanks.

434
00:24:24,810 --> 00:24:28,746
[Phone Ringing]

435
00:24:28,814 --> 00:24:30,907
[Woman On Phone]
Transportation Health Plan.

436
00:24:30,983 --> 00:24:34,578
- It's Gene, KC Trucking. Local 59.
- [Horn Honks]

437
00:24:34,653 --> 00:24:38,589
I got a driver here who's gettin' the
runaround on his kid's hospital bills.

438
00:24:38,657 --> 00:24:41,592
Give me somebody who can
straighten it out, will ya?

439
00:24:41,660 --> 00:24:44,629
- I'll transfer you.
- Yeah, thanks.

440
00:24:44,696 --> 00:24:47,494
- [Making Car Noises]
- Let's see your bear.

441
00:24:47,566 --> 00:24:49,932
- Hi, Margeen!
- Hey, look at you!

442
00:24:50,002 --> 00:24:52,334
- Hi.
- Out of I.C.U. already?

443
00:24:52,404 --> 00:24:54,599
- Yeah.
- They work fast in this place.

444
00:24:54,673 --> 00:24:56,868
Yeah, well,
all except Dr. Stanfield.

445
00:24:56,942 --> 00:24:58,933
- He's a no-show.
- Mmm.

446
00:24:59,011 --> 00:25:01,707
- Have you seen Dave?
- Not today. Isn't he working?

447
00:25:01,780 --> 00:25:04,715
I thought he was gonna take off to
come here. How are the kids?

448
00:25:04,783 --> 00:25:08,219
Oh. Mark's team won three-zip this
morning. He scored the second goal.

449
00:25:08,287 --> 00:25:10,721
And Lynn's at your place
working with Schwartz.

450
00:25:10,789 --> 00:25:13,053
They sent Robbie a little something!
[Chuckles]

451
00:25:13,125 --> 00:25:16,356
- Ooh, what do you say?
- Wanna see what my bed can do?

452
00:25:16,428 --> 00:25:19,329
What do you think
I'm here for?

453
00:25:19,398 --> 00:25:22,231
[Both Laughing]

454
00:25:22,301 --> 00:25:26,135
[Groans, Choking]

455
00:25:27,873 --> 00:25:30,569
Hey! You okay?

456
00:25:30,642 --> 00:25:33,440
- I had another one, Mom.
- Yeah, he's okay.

457
00:25:33,512 --> 00:25:36,447
I know you did, sweetheart.
Come on.

458
00:25:36,515 --> 00:25:39,177
Come on.
We'll take you in.

459
00:25:39,251 --> 00:25:41,185
Hmm?

460
00:25:41,253 --> 00:25:45,019
Mmmm! Oh, boy!

461
00:25:45,090 --> 00:25:48,253
Let's get this
off you now, huh?

462
00:25:48,327 --> 00:25:51,990
Yeah. There you go.

463
00:25:52,064 --> 00:25:54,191
How are you
gettin' through this?

464
00:25:54,266 --> 00:25:58,532
[Sighs]
I'm... gettin' through it.

465
00:25:58,604 --> 00:26:01,835
- [Electric Bed Elevating]
- Ohh!

466
00:26:04,209 --> 00:26:08,373
[Laughing]
Oooh!

467
00:26:08,447 --> 00:26:11,541
Cool!
[Laughing]

468
00:26:11,617 --> 00:26:15,451
Oh, here's stuff. A change of clothes,
some potato salad from lunch.

469
00:26:15,520 --> 00:26:18,011
- Ohh.
- I'm 20 minutes late.

470
00:26:18,090 --> 00:26:21,389
- How am I gonna repay you?
- You're not.

471
00:26:21,460 --> 00:26:25,362
Mmmm. You're in my debt
for life.

472
00:26:25,430 --> 00:26:27,921
[Lori Laughs]
I think so.

473
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:30,468
- Bye, Margeen.
- Bye-bye.

474
00:26:30,535 --> 00:26:32,594
Bye. Let's see
what she's got here.

475
00:26:32,671 --> 00:26:35,697
Ooh, gummi bears!

476
00:26:35,774 --> 00:26:38,242
[Robbie]
Can I have this one?

477
00:26:38,310 --> 00:26:40,744
[Lori] Oh, you're gonna make me
dig down to the bottom?

478
00:26:40,812 --> 00:26:43,246
[Woman]
Do you want to check the Reimuller boy?

479
00:26:43,315 --> 00:26:46,546
[Chattering]

480
00:26:48,220 --> 00:26:50,950
So, you're leaving us
tomorrow, huh?

481
00:26:51,023 --> 00:26:53,321
No.

482
00:26:53,392 --> 00:26:55,758
Well, that's
what it says here.

483
00:26:55,827 --> 00:26:59,058
No, he was transferred here
to be evaluated by Dr. Stanfield.

484
00:26:59,131 --> 00:27:01,691
He hasn't even seen him yet.

485
00:27:01,767 --> 00:27:04,327
I'll make a note of it.

486
00:27:04,403 --> 00:27:07,429
[P.A., Indistinct]

487
00:27:07,506 --> 00:27:10,168
- Hi, Dad.
- Hi, guy.

488
00:27:10,242 --> 00:27:14,008
- [Making Airplane Sounds]
- Hey, where've you been?

489
00:27:15,347 --> 00:27:19,078
[Sighs]
We have no insurance.

490
00:27:19,151 --> 00:27:21,949
What?

491
00:27:22,020 --> 00:27:25,581
Yeah, when I changed locals, there was a
six-month "no benefits" period.

492
00:27:25,657 --> 00:27:27,591
It's not up for a month.

493
00:27:27,659 --> 00:27:31,151
And after that they won't
cover him because he'll have
a pre-existing condition.

494
00:27:31,229 --> 00:27:35,996
No. Nobody-- Nobody ever said anything
about a "no benefits" period!

495
00:27:39,972 --> 00:27:42,099
Supposedly, we were notified.

496
00:27:42,174 --> 00:27:46,804
I read the fine print, Dave, and I do
keep records. We were not notified.

497
00:27:46,878 --> 00:27:49,369
That's their policy.

498
00:27:49,448 --> 00:27:53,748
That's why. That's why
Robbie's transferred out of I.C.U.!

499
00:27:53,819 --> 00:27:56,583
I'll bet you that's why Stanfield
never showed up too!

500
00:27:56,655 --> 00:27:59,920
And I'll bet you that's why they're
gonna kick us outta here!

501
00:27:59,992 --> 00:28:03,155
Oh. So what are we
supposed to do now?

502
00:28:03,228 --> 00:28:06,493
Well, what people
that don't have insurance do.
We take him to County Hospital.

503
00:28:06,565 --> 00:28:08,999
And you're just
gonna accept that?

504
00:28:09,067 --> 00:28:12,696
- Do you have a better idea?
- Yeah, I do!

505
00:28:14,473 --> 00:28:18,000
Hey, wanna see my truck?
[Grunting]

506
00:28:18,076 --> 00:28:20,840
- Kansas City.
- [Robbie] That's not your truck, Dad.

507
00:28:20,912 --> 00:28:22,971
Transportation Health Plan.

508
00:28:23,048 --> 00:28:26,745
Hey! That's
a flammables carrier, Dave!

509
00:28:26,818 --> 00:28:29,150
Yeah. I put in
to drive nights.

510
00:28:29,221 --> 00:28:31,883
No way. No way!
You promised!

511
00:28:31,957 --> 00:28:35,552
- We agreed you would never--
- You know how many thousands
of dollars we are in the hole?

512
00:28:35,627 --> 00:28:38,960
Well, I'll take a telephone sales job
where I could work at home.

513
00:28:39,031 --> 00:28:42,899
We could go on welfare!
But you are not gonna drive
a flammables carrier!

514
00:28:42,968 --> 00:28:45,402
- My family is not going on welfare!
- [Robbie Crying]

515
00:28:45,470 --> 00:28:48,405
There's no way you could make a dent
in our debt with hazard pay!

516
00:28:48,473 --> 00:28:51,408
- Do you know why they call it
hazard pay in the first place?
- [Crying Continues]

517
00:28:51,476 --> 00:28:55,412
Why don't you just take a rider on your
life insurance and live off of that?

518
00:28:55,480 --> 00:28:58,711
- Stop yelling!
- What am I supposed to do,
Lori, huh? Huh?

519
00:28:58,784 --> 00:29:01,912
What in the hell
do you want me to do?

520
00:29:01,987 --> 00:29:05,514
[Lori Sobbing]

521
00:29:05,590 --> 00:29:09,026
- [P.A., Indistinct]
- [Door Slams]

522
00:29:09,094 --> 00:29:12,029
[Sobbing Continues]

523
00:29:19,938 --> 00:29:24,773
##[Radio Playing
Country Music]

524
00:29:35,387 --> 00:29:37,753
[Schwartz Whinnies]

525
00:29:37,823 --> 00:29:40,849
[Dog Barking]

526
00:29:47,399 --> 00:29:50,766
##[Radio Continues]

527
00:29:54,806 --> 00:29:57,138
[Engine, Music Stops]

528
00:29:59,478 --> 00:30:01,446
[Dog Continues Barking]

529
00:30:04,616 --> 00:30:07,744
Oh, no.
Oh, damn it.

530
00:30:07,819 --> 00:30:10,617
[Grunts]

531
00:30:28,907 --> 00:30:31,205
[Barking Continues]

532
00:30:53,532 --> 00:30:56,330
[Tires Screeching]

533
00:31:00,272 --> 00:31:03,036
[Panting]

534
00:31:05,610 --> 00:31:07,544
[Footsteps]

535
00:31:13,385 --> 00:31:16,149
[Clock Ticking]

536
00:31:17,289 --> 00:31:19,223
[Sighs]

537
00:31:36,474 --> 00:31:40,001
[Lori]
Okay. Dilantin.

538
00:31:40,078 --> 00:31:43,241
A hundred milligrams.
That a boy.

539
00:31:43,315 --> 00:31:45,875
And Tegretol.

540
00:31:47,886 --> 00:31:50,218
A hundred milligrams.
That's it. Good boy.

541
00:31:50,288 --> 00:31:53,519
- And the depakene.
- I don't want that.

542
00:31:53,592 --> 00:31:56,618
- I know, honey.
- It tastes yucky.
It makes my tummy hurt.

543
00:31:56,695 --> 00:31:59,027
I know, darling, but I got
a new medicine for that.

544
00:31:59,097 --> 00:32:01,895
Come on.
[Making Airplane Noises]

545
00:32:01,967 --> 00:32:04,231
[Laughs]
That's a boy.

546
00:32:04,302 --> 00:32:06,566
- [Mark] Foreclosure?
- [Dave] They take our house.

547
00:32:06,638 --> 00:32:09,038
[Mark]
What do you mean, they take our
house back? It's our house.

548
00:32:09,107 --> 00:32:11,541
Yeah, as long as we make
the payments.

549
00:32:11,610 --> 00:32:13,544
Well, don't we?

550
00:32:13,612 --> 00:32:16,479
When we can,
as much as we can.

551
00:32:16,548 --> 00:32:21,247
We have to pay the hospitals first,
or, uh, they'll take my pay.

552
00:32:21,319 --> 00:32:25,153
How can they take your pay?
You earned that!

553
00:32:25,223 --> 00:32:28,249
Well, they earned it too,
taking care of Robbie.

554
00:32:28,326 --> 00:32:32,524
Come on, kids.
The bus'll be here in a second.
We can talk about this later.

555
00:32:32,597 --> 00:32:37,261
[Coughing, Gasping]

556
00:32:37,335 --> 00:32:40,998
Okay, okay, Rob.
I'm here, honey.

557
00:32:41,072 --> 00:32:44,098
I'm here.
That's okay.

558
00:32:49,347 --> 00:32:53,977
So, what happens when the bank
takes back the title of our
house, or whatever you said?

559
00:32:54,052 --> 00:32:56,850
- They'll sell it.
- They'll sell it?

560
00:32:56,921 --> 00:33:00,118
Where are we
supposed to live?

561
00:33:00,191 --> 00:33:03,490
What about the animals?
What about Schwartz?

562
00:33:03,561 --> 00:33:07,361
- I don't wanna sell our house.
- I know, honey.

563
00:33:07,432 --> 00:33:09,992
- And what, you're just gonna let them?
- Mark!

564
00:33:10,068 --> 00:33:13,697
I'll do everything I can
to keep our house.

565
00:33:13,772 --> 00:33:16,764
I could use some support.

566
00:33:18,443 --> 00:33:20,604
Fine. I'm sorry.

567
00:33:20,679 --> 00:33:23,375
[Groaning]

568
00:33:23,448 --> 00:33:25,382
Lynn? Lynn?

569
00:33:25,450 --> 00:33:28,942
[Coughing, Groaning]

570
00:33:29,020 --> 00:33:31,454
- [Sighs]
- [Door Closes]

571
00:33:35,126 --> 00:33:40,063
[Man] Let's see. Um, do you have any
untapped financial resources?

572
00:33:40,131 --> 00:33:43,760
Savings, investments,
family?

573
00:33:43,835 --> 00:33:47,271
Well, uh, we've already
gone through our savings.

574
00:33:47,339 --> 00:33:49,364
All we have left is the farm.

575
00:33:50,909 --> 00:33:54,242
[Sighs] We're not in the business
of taking people's homes.

576
00:33:54,312 --> 00:33:57,509
We'd much rather
work something out.

577
00:33:57,582 --> 00:34:01,541
What kind of payments do you think
you can handle, say, half-monthly?

578
00:34:03,822 --> 00:34:07,883
Well...
[Sighing]

579
00:34:11,429 --> 00:34:13,727
...that's how much
I have today.

580
00:34:15,567 --> 00:34:18,730
I don't know
about next month.

581
00:34:18,803 --> 00:34:21,567
Come on, Lori.

582
00:34:29,647 --> 00:34:32,616
- [Whinnying]
- Come on, sweetie.

583
00:34:35,153 --> 00:34:37,587
I want to pet him.

584
00:34:43,528 --> 00:34:45,860
[Dog Barking]

585
00:34:53,338 --> 00:34:57,434
- Can I ride him?
- [Neighing]

586
00:34:57,509 --> 00:35:01,536
Someday. I promise.

587
00:35:01,613 --> 00:35:04,480
Scout's honor?

588
00:35:06,117 --> 00:35:08,278
Scout's honor.

589
00:35:15,460 --> 00:35:18,020
[Lynn]
Mom is gonna be so excited!

590
00:35:18,096 --> 00:35:21,293
- [Mark] I get to tell her first.
- Okay.

591
00:35:25,103 --> 00:35:27,901
Hey, where were you guys,
huh? Huh?

592
00:35:27,972 --> 00:35:31,100
I called and I called
from the doctor's office...

593
00:35:31,176 --> 00:35:33,736
...to get Daddy to pick up
Robbie's prescription.

594
00:35:33,812 --> 00:35:36,576
And the phone rang and rang,
and nobody answered it.

595
00:35:36,648 --> 00:35:40,311
We were here. Maybe you dialed wrong.
What did the doctor say?

596
00:35:40,385 --> 00:35:43,479
Well, it's not measles.
You want that?

597
00:35:43,555 --> 00:35:46,080
It's Stevens-Johnson's Syndrome...

598
00:35:46,157 --> 00:35:49,285
...one of the rare
side effects of Tegretol.

599
00:35:49,360 --> 00:35:51,760
I don't know why
they call 'em side effects.

600
00:35:51,830 --> 00:35:56,028
As if a 102 temperature
and a rash over his whole entire body...

601
00:35:56,100 --> 00:35:59,194
...is somethin' off
to the side somewhere.

602
00:36:00,939 --> 00:36:02,839
Did I forget
somebody's birthday?

603
00:36:02,907 --> 00:36:07,276
No, it's something else.
We're gonna wait for Dad.

604
00:36:09,747 --> 00:36:13,239
[Sighs]
What is wrong with this--

605
00:36:13,318 --> 00:36:16,219
Oh, my God!

606
00:36:16,287 --> 00:36:19,882
What time is it?
I still have time.

607
00:36:19,958 --> 00:36:22,791
- Lynn, do you have any money?
- Uh, a couple of dollars.

608
00:36:22,861 --> 00:36:25,523
- Never mind. I think--
- What are you doing?

609
00:36:25,597 --> 00:36:28,532
The phone's turned off.
We didn't pay the bill.

610
00:36:28,600 --> 00:36:32,331
Well, good. We won't be waked up by
stupid people yelling we owe them money!

611
00:36:32,403 --> 00:36:35,497
- I have ten minutes.
Will you watch him for me?
- Uh-huh.

612
00:36:35,573 --> 00:36:38,508
You can't take money out of there.
No one touches that money!

613
00:36:38,576 --> 00:36:41,739
We have to have a phone, Mark.
What if Robbie needs 911?

614
00:36:41,813 --> 00:36:43,747
No, this is for our trip!

615
00:36:43,815 --> 00:36:47,012
What trip?
Mark, look at your brother!

616
00:36:47,085 --> 00:36:50,350
You really think we're gonna
take him on a trip?

617
00:36:50,421 --> 00:36:54,323
When they kick us out of our
house, you think we're gonna
go on vacation?

618
00:36:54,392 --> 00:36:56,952
Oh, well, I thought since
I got an "A" in English...

619
00:36:57,028 --> 00:37:00,725
...we'd be going to Hawaii and
taking diving lessons like Dad said.

620
00:37:00,798 --> 00:37:03,665
- Dumb me!
- Oh, honey, I'm sorry.

621
00:37:03,735 --> 00:37:06,602
Me too! I'm sorry
Robbie was ever born!

622
00:37:06,671 --> 00:37:10,163
- Don't say that!
- If he's gonna die,
why doesn't he do it?

623
00:37:10,241 --> 00:37:12,937
Mark!

624
00:37:13,011 --> 00:37:17,573
Mark! Mark!

625
00:37:17,649 --> 00:37:20,846
[Lynn]
Mom, Robbie's having a seizure!

626
00:37:20,919 --> 00:37:22,887
Mark!

627
00:37:22,954 --> 00:37:26,515
Mom, it's a bad one!

628
00:37:26,591 --> 00:37:31,221
[Loud Whimpering]

629
00:37:31,296 --> 00:37:34,527
Okay. Okay, darling.

630
00:37:34,599 --> 00:37:38,091
It's okay.
It's over.

631
00:37:41,639 --> 00:37:44,733
- [Robbie Gasping, Choking]
- He's doing it again.

632
00:37:44,809 --> 00:37:48,506
[Gasping Continues]

633
00:37:54,018 --> 00:37:57,613
It's okay.
It's okay, honey.

634
00:37:59,190 --> 00:38:01,658
It's okay.
We're here.

635
00:38:01,726 --> 00:38:04,194
It's okay.

636
00:38:04,262 --> 00:38:06,560
It's okay, sweetie.

637
00:38:11,102 --> 00:38:13,036
[Siren Wails]

638
00:38:18,276 --> 00:38:22,110
[Woman On P.A.]
County Hospital cafeteria
will be closed in ten minutes.

639
00:38:25,783 --> 00:38:28,911
[Man On P.A., Indistinct]

640
00:38:33,758 --> 00:38:36,784
- I'm Dr. Abbasac.
- Hi.

641
00:38:38,963 --> 00:38:43,400
Robbie's failed to respond
to most of the usual
anticonvulsive medications.

642
00:38:43,468 --> 00:38:46,562
The problem's compounded by the fact
that he has multiple seizure types.

643
00:38:46,638 --> 00:38:49,106
We're gonna try some
less commonly used drugs.

644
00:38:51,075 --> 00:38:54,101
What about
a compassionate use program?

645
00:38:54,178 --> 00:38:59,115
I see no reason to use
an unproven drug when there are
proven ones left to try.

646
00:38:59,183 --> 00:39:01,617
I'm ordering a series of tests
for tomorrow morning.

647
00:39:01,686 --> 00:39:03,847
We'll repeat them
on a regular basis...

648
00:39:03,921 --> 00:39:06,856
...to monitor changes as we begin
the new med regimens.

649
00:39:06,924 --> 00:39:09,688
- Is that necessary?
- Is what necessary?

650
00:39:09,761 --> 00:39:13,197
Well, he's had the same tests over and
over, and they're pretty hard on him.

651
00:39:13,264 --> 00:39:15,198
- Yeah.
- They always turn out the same.

652
00:39:15,266 --> 00:39:18,201
There's something I should make
very clear to both of you.

653
00:39:18,269 --> 00:39:20,897
After a first
antiepileptic drug fails...

654
00:39:20,972 --> 00:39:23,702
...there's only a 15 percent chance
the drugs will ever work.

655
00:39:23,775 --> 00:39:25,902
After that,
there's only surgery.

656
00:39:25,977 --> 00:39:28,969
You shouldn't expect this
to be easy.

657
00:39:29,047 --> 00:39:33,108
[Sighs] Why not? So far
it's been a piece of cake.

658
00:39:34,786 --> 00:39:37,220
Robbie's what I consider
a high-stakes case.

659
00:39:37,288 --> 00:39:42,055
If I can stop his seizures,
he still has a very good chance
for a normal, healthy life.

660
00:39:42,126 --> 00:39:46,187
But a young brain can't tolerate
seizures of his intensity
and frequency indefinitely.

661
00:39:46,264 --> 00:39:49,597
Well, what if you
can't stop them?

662
00:39:49,667 --> 00:39:51,601
There are no
hard and fast rules...

663
00:39:51,669 --> 00:39:54,729
...but it's not unusual to find
neurological compromises:

664
00:39:54,806 --> 00:39:57,934
diminished capacity,
developmental delays...

665
00:39:58,009 --> 00:39:59,943
progressive retardation.

666
00:40:02,480 --> 00:40:06,610
- [Sighs]
- Excuse me.

667
00:40:08,653 --> 00:40:11,918
[Man On P.A., Indistinct]

668
00:40:25,503 --> 00:40:28,233
Not much of a view, huh?

669
00:40:28,306 --> 00:40:30,968
[Laughs]
No.

670
00:40:34,011 --> 00:40:36,707
- Your boy has seizures?
- Yeah.

671
00:40:36,781 --> 00:40:39,978
That's what Lili had.
They did brain surgery.

672
00:40:40,051 --> 00:40:42,042
Oh.

673
00:40:42,120 --> 00:40:44,611
How is she doing?

674
00:40:44,689 --> 00:40:46,657
Okay, I guess.

675
00:40:46,724 --> 00:40:49,625
She's a beautiful little girl.

676
00:40:49,694 --> 00:40:52,788
And I checked with several colleagues
from across the country...

677
00:40:52,864 --> 00:40:55,298
...all of them very accomplished
neurologists.

678
00:40:55,366 --> 00:40:58,802
A few of them run pediatric
neurology departments at major
med schools and hospitals.

679
00:40:58,870 --> 00:41:01,236
It sounds like you're in very good hands
right where you are.

680
00:41:01,305 --> 00:41:03,432
Uh-huh. Okay.

681
00:41:03,508 --> 00:41:07,171
They differ slightly in the order
that they try the drugs.

682
00:41:07,245 --> 00:41:10,908
After that, there's surgery, but
you're not ready for that yet.

683
00:41:10,982 --> 00:41:14,679
- Oh, no, we are not.
- Oh, Lori, one other thing
they did agree on:

684
00:41:14,752 --> 00:41:17,983
Treating seizures in kids
is much more art than science.

685
00:41:18,055 --> 00:41:22,651
- [Robbie Grunting]
- Okay, Doc, thanks. Bye.

686
00:41:22,727 --> 00:41:27,596
I'll put a request in
to Dr. Abbasac for a stool softener.

687
00:41:27,665 --> 00:41:29,826
That should help.

688
00:41:29,901 --> 00:41:32,131
Why does he have hemorrhoids?

689
00:41:32,203 --> 00:41:34,364
The medication causes
the constipation...

690
00:41:34,438 --> 00:41:37,305
...and the pushing
causes the hemorrhoids.

691
00:41:43,781 --> 00:41:45,772
##[Radio]

692
00:41:45,850 --> 00:41:48,944
#Hey, little pretty girl#

